<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="visualizing_varieties" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Visualizing Varieties</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      These are some basic varieties that we can visualize over <m>\R</m>.
      The SageMath code below can be reused with the appropriate modifications to visualize other varieties, provided that they live an affine space of dimension at most 3.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="visualizing_curves">
    <title>Basic Curves</title>
    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Sketch the variety defined by the polynomial equation <m>x^2 + y^2 - 1 = 0</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
	<p>
	  In Sage, we can visualize equations in affine 2-space using the <c>implicit_plot</c> function.
	  By default, Sage knows to treat <c>x</c> as a variable.
	  If you want to use other variables, you will need to declare them using the command <c>var('var_name_1, var_name_2, ...')</c>.
	  The function <c>implicit_plot</c> expects, at a minimum, the following arguments:
	  <ol>
	    <li>
	      An equation of the form <c>expression_1 == expression_2</c>.
	      Sage interprets a single <c>expression</c> as <c>expression == 0</c>.
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      For each variable, a range of allowable values expressed as a triple <c>(var_name, min_value, max_value)</c>.
	    </li>
	  </ol>
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y')
	    implicit_plot(x^2 + y^2 - 1, (x,-1,1), (y,-1,1))
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<p>
	  There are several other optional parameters.
	  You can find documentation on these parameters using the <c>?</c> operator as below.
	  This will work for any Sage function, although the helpfulness depends on how well the function was documented by the author.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>implicit_plot?</input>
	</sage>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Sketch the variety defined by the polynomial equation <m>xy - x^3 + 1 = 0</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
	<p>
	  Note that we can separate the variables in this equation to see that this is just the rational function
	  <md>y = \frac{x^3 - 1}{x} = \frac{(x - 1)(x^2 + x + 1)}{x}</md>
	  We could use <c>implicit_plot</c> to visualize the variety directly, but we can also use the simpler <c>plot</c> function.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    plot((x^3 - 1)/x, (-5,5))
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="visualizing_surfaces">
    <title>Surfaces</title>
    <p>
      For the basic curves above, Sage is overkill.
      However, it is quite handy for surfaces.
      The main tool we will need is <c>implicit_plot3d</c>, which works essentially the same way, but allows expressions with up to three variables.
      We will utilize the variables <c>x</c>, <c>y</c>, and <c>z</c> using <c>var('x,y,z')</c>, but there's nothing particularly special about these naems.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Sketch the variety defined by the poylnomial equation <m>z - x^2 - y^2 = 0</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y,z')
	    implicit_plot3d(z - x^2 - y^2, (x,-1,1), (y,-1,1), (z,0,1))
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Sketch the variety defined by the polynomial equation <m>z^2 - x^2 - y^2 = 0</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y,z')
	    implicit_plot3d(z^2 - x^2 - y^2, (x,-1,1), (y,-1,1), (z,-1,1))
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Sketch the variety defined by <m>x^2 - y^2z^2 + z^3 = 0</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
	<p>
	  If you're following along in the book, you'll likely notice that the result of the following command doesn't quite match the picture in the text.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y,z')
	    implicit_plot3d(x^2 - y^2*z^2 + z^3 == 0, (x,-1,1), (y,-1,1), (z,-1,1))
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<p>
	  The reason for this is <m>f = x^2 - y^2z^2 + z^3</m> is not smooth.
	  In particular, we can see the gradient vanishes along the <m>y</m>-axis, which is where most of the funny business happens.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y,z')
	    g(x,y,z) = (x^2 - y^2*z^2 + z^3).gradient()
	    print(g(x,y,z))
	    print(g(0,y,0))
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<p>
	  We can fix some of this using parameterization.
	  From the text, we have the parameterization
	  <md>
	    <mrow>x \amp= t(u^2 - t^2)</mrow>
	    <mrow>y \amp= u</mrow>
	    <mrow>z \amp= u^2 - t^2</mrow>
	  </md>
	  The following sage code plots this parameterization using the <c>parametric_plot3d</c> function.
	  The <c>colormap</c> feature here is unnecessary, but provides a nice visualization of the grandient on the surface: the gradient is normalized to the interval <m>[0,1]</m>, with red assigned to 0, and blue assigned to 1.
	  The deepeer the shade, the closer to normalized gradient value is to the boundary of <m>[0,1]</m>
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    var('x,y,z,t,u')
	    f_x = t*(u^2 - t^2)
	    f_y = u
	    f_z = u^2 - t^2

	    f = x^2 - y^2*z^2 + z^3

	    grad_f = [diff(f,x), diff(f,y), diff(f,z)]
	    grad_norm = sqrt(sum(g^2 for g in grad_f))
	    grad_param = grad_norm.subs({x:f_x, y:f_y, z:f_z})

	    parametric_plot3d([f_x,f_y,f_z],
            (u,-1,1), (t,-1,1),
            mesh=true,
            color=(lambda t, u: grad_param.subs({SR.var('t'): t, SR.var('u'): u}).n(), colormaps.RdBu))
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<p>
	  Note that the parameterized version makes it easy to see that the vanishing of the gradient is happening where the surface pinches together.
	  This is an example of <term>singular locus</term><mdash/>we will encounter singularities later.
	</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="visualizing_the_twisted_cubic">
    <title>The Twisted Cubic</title>
    <p>
      In affine two-space, a single equation defines a curve, which is intuitively a one-dimensional object.
      In three-space, a single polynomial equation defines a surface, which is intuitively a two-dimensional object.
      To obtain a curve in three-space, we will need at least two equations.
      Geometrically, this means curves are obtained by intersecting surfaces.
    </p>
    <p>
      One particularly interesting curve is called the <em>twisted cubic</em>.
      This curve is obtained by intersecting a parabolic cylinder with a cubic cylinder:
      <md>V(y - x^2, z - x^3)</md>.
      Since this variety is defined to be the points <m>(x,y,z)</m> satisfying <m>y - x^2 = z - x^3 = 0</m>, we can easily parameterize this curve using
      <md>
	<mrow>x \amp= t</mrow>
	<mrow>y \amp= t^2</mrow>
	<mrow>z \amp= t^3</mrow>
      </md>
      This allows us to plot the curve using the <c>parametric_plot3d</c> function.
      We can visualize the construction of the twisted cubic as an intersection by plotting the two surfaces <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>z = x^3</m> along with the twisted cubic.
      Note that the <c>+</c> operator in Sage is overloaded to allow <q>addition</q> of plots, which means simply display the summed plots in the same window.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	var('x,y,z,t')
	f_1, f_2 = y - x^2, z - x^3
	I = (x,-5,5)
	J = (y,-5,5)
	K = (z,-5,5)
	implicit_plot3d(f_1, I, J, K,color='red',opacity=0.5) +\
	implicit_plot3d(f_2,I,J,K,opacity=0.5) +\
	parametric_plot3d([t,t^2,t^3], (t,-5^(1/3),5^(1/3)),color='black',thickness=5)
      </input>
    </sage>
    <p>
      Note also the usage of <c>\</c> and a carriage return to help minimize horizontal spread.
      It is important to ensure that no whitespace is added after the slash, as this will generate the error message
      <q>SyntaxError: unexpected character after line continuation character</q>, as below.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	var('x,y')
	#This is fine.
	good = x +\
	y
	# The space following \ causes an error.
	bad = x +\ 
	y
      </input>
    </sage>
  </subsection>
</section>
